@juliusbierk @emmanuelle would this example not be better off as a gallery example? It seems a bit long-winded for a docstring.

If we want to keep it a docstring, I would suggest breaking it up with comments describing each section (making the image, using the filter, etc.)

Thoughts?

@kne42 yes, it's a big problem, but we absolutely do have that problem. Because NumPy docstrings are not automatically checked in any way, it is guaranteed that some proportion of them will be incorrect. "If it's not tested, it's broken" is a very good rule of thumb. At the very least, our annotations are woefully incomplete.

@chrisconlan we definitely would welcome manual annotations. However I think we need to have a major discussion about the best syntax for them. At scikit-image, we don't yet have a process for proposing major changes, but we are working on one. In the coming weeks I'll work on a proposal for a proposal template :stuck_out_tongue: and we can discuss an annotation proposal.

Three specific concerns I have:
- we should aim to be compatible with https://github.com/numpy/numpy-stubs, even though they are just experimental for now.
- I'm wondering whether we can add some kind of semantic information to our types. For example, an Array2D can be a grayscale image, or it can be a list of coordinates. Should we make two separate typedefs for this?
- Similarly, an Array3D can be a multichannel 2D image or it can be a 3D grayscale image. Also, some algorithms take an nD image: do we add an ArrayND type that encompasses any dimension/shape?

@kne42 regarding automatic annotations, I propose the following:
- the automatic annotator should ignore signatures that already have type annotations
- the automatic annotator should fail when it doesn't understand a signature, and point users to the signature so that it can be manually annotated.

@lnielsen it's a fair point for the library. That's why I didn't use `detect_identifier_schemes` but rather wrote some ugly workarounds for getting things decently normalized when porting from legacy.

As I later spoke with @kaplun, it seems that this is actually a INSPIRE use-case in which we harvested lots of __arXiv references__ when we actually wanted only the __identifiers__. I'd rather leave the workaround in our repo until we have things migrated rather than cluttering `idutils` with a specific logic.

Our code would "write" better if the `arxiv identifier` regex would also accept `arxiv identifiers` so even if I added some __reference__ specific code here I would still need the use-case in which I transform references into identifiers.

