It appears because the compiler is called with both the proper directories like `-isysroot /crystax-ndk/platforms/android-19/arch-arm/` and `-I-I/crystax-ndk/platforms/android-19/arch-arm`, but also this one: `-I/usr/include`, it seems that it picks up `/usr/include/stdlib.h` instead of a proper choice like `/crystax-ndk/platforms/android-19/arch-arm/usr/include/stdlib.h` (which is also in the include path) - and as a result, tries to compile standard lib code that is meant for Linux and not for Android.

So the order or something about the `-I` arguments probably needs to be changed. But I'm not sure what exactly, or how to make `p4a` do that (since not all of them are generated by the recipe itself).

@a-campbell wrote in #224:
"To ensure pyfolio is being passed correctly formatted inputs, it might be helpful to run returns, positions, and transactions through validation functions before the rest of pyfolio runs. These functions would check the column names, datatypes, datetime formats, and presence of nans in the returns, positions, transactions and gross leverage DataFrames.

Checking inputs upfront will allow us to show the user better error messaging when an improperly formatted input is passed. These validation functions could also be used in the integration tests of libraries that depend on pyfolio. If/when we change the input requirements of pyfolio, we'd wan't deprecated integrations to fail elegantly in tests, rather than hard to decipher seaborn tracebacks in production."

@cbenz : j'ai besoin de réformes partout (indirectètaxation, tunisia etc) ;-)
Je ne comprends pas bien l'argument qui justifie de mettre les réformes en cache pour accélérer les tests 
mais estime que cela n'est pas nécessaires quand on utilise _vraiment_ les réformes.

@benjello Thanks!

Do you know why there was a `NaN` in the first place by the way?
I'd like to understand how I could have guessed the solution (setting `heures_remunerees_volume`).

@asqui - no worries, for a small part of the package, this module has a number of issues, and a lot of the fixes that get merged end up stepping on or breaking something else. It probably wouldn't hurt to write some test cases for this!

And I ended up submitting a seperate pull request anyway, since, while this merge request was a no-op, someone else actually submitted the same line change as part of their own pull request, which *was* merged :-P

Really, the config file parsing needs to be fixed to account for the fact that some config options should be treated as booleans, otherwise the "if oath['oauth_dance']" test will always evaluate to True if that option is only specified in the jirashell.init config file, since options are treated as strings.

